  "Idea": "IMEF-Gen (Iterative Meta-Evaluation Framework with Generative Reference Expansion) reimagines NLG evaluation as a co-evolutionary process between metrics and reference corpora. Traditional evaluation frameworks assume fixed reference sets, leading to biased correlation estimates and poor generalization when real-world output diversity exceeds the narrow scope of available references. IMEF-Gen addresses this by introducing a dual-loop architecture: an outer loop that dynamically expands and refines the reference corpus using generative augmentation, and an inner loop that iteratively evaluates and improves candidate metrics using a multi-dimensional meta-evaluator. In the outer loop, an LLM-based Reference Diversifier generates alternative valid outputs for each source input (e.g., summary, essay, dialogue response), guided by constraints derived from semantic equivalence, syntactic variation, and discourse coherence. Generated candidates undergo adversarial validation via a discriminator trained to distinguish human-written from machine-generated references and are filtered using redundancy detection and semantic clustering to ensure quality and diversity. Validated references are incrementally incorporated into the benchmark, forming a progressively richer semantic canvas. In the inner loop, candidate metrics are evaluated across four evolving dimensions: (1) Correlation — tracked against human judgments over time as references expand; (2) Generalization — measured by performance stability across domains and reference richness levels; (3) Robustness — tested against perturbations and sensitivity to reference inflation; and (4) Coherence Judgment — assessed via logical consistency in ranking outputs under expanded reference conditions. A Generative Feedback Model, trained on historical 'metric failure → fix' trajectories and augmented with insights from educational feedback systems like LEAF, produces interpretable diagnostics and repair suggestions. Crucially, metric performance degradation upon reference expansion becomes a new signal for brittleness, triggering refinement via neural architecture search or prompt optimization. The two loops interact symbiotically: improved metrics better guide reference selection (e.g., identifying under-covered regions), while richer references expose latent flaws in metrics. This closed, adaptive system enables the emergence of evaluation standards that are not only more aligned with human judgment but also resilient to linguistic variation and domain shifts. IMEF-Gen has broad implications for benchmark design, model development, and trustworthy AI, particularly in high-stakes applications such as education, healthcare, and legal text generation where evaluation validity is paramount.",
